The paper proposes a cognitively-inspired agent-based service composition model that focuses on bounded rationality rather than optimality. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Multiagent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category, which deals with the study of systems composed of multiple interacting intelligent agents. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of artificial intelligence techniques, such as decision-making and filtering, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also deals with the challenges of distributed computing, which could place it in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also mentions conflicting goals from multiple users, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of complex systems with multiple objectives. Finally, the paper mentions the evaluation of the proposed approach, which suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category, which deals with the study of efficient algorithms and data structures for solving computational problems.
